  "prompt": "I didn't kiss on the first date, is this bad and what should I do from this point on?",
  "response": "Not kissing on the first date is **absolutely not bad**\u2014in fact, it\u2019s a personal choice and completely normal. Everyone moves at their own pace when it comes to physical intimacy, and there\u2019s no rule that says you have to kiss on the first date. What matters most is how you both feel about the connection and your comfort levels.\n\nHere\u2019s what you can do moving forward:\n\n### 1. **Reflect on How You Feel**\n   - Did you *want* to kiss them but held back? If so, that\u2019s okay\u2014there\u2019s always the next date.\n   - Were you unsure about your feelings or not ready? That\u2019s valid too. Take your time.\n\n### 2. **Focus on Communication**\n   - If you\u2019re interested in seeing them again, let them know! A simple message like, *\u201cI had a great time with you\u2014would love to see you again,\u201d* can go a long way.\n   - If they\u2019re interested in you, they\u2019ll appreciate the clarity and effort.\n\n### 3. **Plan a Second Date**\n   - Use the second date to deepen your connection. If you feel comfortable, you can initiate a kiss then\u2014if it feels right.\n   - If you\u2019re still unsure, that\u2019s fine too. Take things at your own pace.\n\n### 4. **Don\u2019t Overthink It**\n   - Remember, a first date is about getting to know each other. Physical affection is just one part of building a connection, and it\u2019s not a measure of success or failure.\n\n### 5. **Be True to Yourself**\n   - Don\u2019t feel pressured to do anything you\u2019re not ready for. A healthy relationship is built on mutual respect and understanding.\n\nIn the end, what\u2019s most important is that you\u2019re comfortable and true to yourself. The right person will respect your boundaries and appreciate you for who you are. \ud83c\udf1f",
  "temperature": 1.0,
